Interface KNDLSerialComm

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    KNDLSerialCommImpl

    public interface KNDLSerialComm
    Interface to communicate with a control device. Go to https://github.com/abdonvivas/KNDL for more information.
    Author:
    Abdón Alejandro Vivas Imparato

        void sendData(java.lang.String data)
       throws java.lang.Exception
        Sends a string to the serial port.
        This method does not opens, nor closes a serial port. To open or close a serial port, use openSerialPort() and closeSerialPort().
        Parameters:
        data - The String to be sent.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - If something goes wrong during the sending of the data.

      • receiveData

        java.lang.String receiveData()
                      throws java.lang.Exception
        Receives data from the serial port.
        Any implementation of this method must be a semi-blocking call. In other words, the read call must always return at least 1 byte of data without blocking indefinitely. Use SERIAL_COMM_TIMEOUT to prevent blocking indefinitely during your implementation.
        This method does not opens, nor closes a serial port. To open or close a serial port, use openSerialPort() and closeSerialPort().
        Returns:
        A string representation of the data received from the serial port.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - If something goes wrong during the receiving of the data.

      • getComPorts

        java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> getComPorts()
        Returns an ArrayList<String> with the system-defined port names of all the available serial ports with connected devices (e.g. COM1, ttyS0,...).
        Returns:
        A list with the system-defined port names of the available serial ports with connected devices.

      • getComPortDescriptions

        java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> getComPortDescriptions()
        Returns an ArrayList<String> with the descriptions of the devices connected to the available serial ports. This descriptions are generated by the operating system and may not be a good representation of the devices described. If you are implementing this method and for some reason you can't obtain the device descriptions, then make a call to getComPorts() and return its results.
        Returns:
        A list with the descriptions of the devices connected to the available serial ports.

      • getComPortDescription

        java.lang.String getComPortDescription(java.lang.String portName)
        Returns the description of the device connected to the serial port with portName. If you are implementing this method and for some reason you can't obtain the device descriptions, return an empty string.
        Parameters:
        portName - The system-defined name (e.g. COM1, ttyS0,...) of the port.
        Returns:
        The description of the port with portName

      • checkSerialPort

        boolean checkSerialPort(java.lang.String portName)
        Checks if the port with the specified specified port name is between the available serial ports with connected devices.
        Parameters:
        portName - The system-defined name (e.g. COM1, ttyS0,...) of the port to be checked.
        Returns:
        True, if portName is within the available serial ports. False if it is not.

      • matchRegEx

        java.lang.String matchRegEx(java.lang.String regularExpression)
        Attempts to match the specified regular expression against all of the descriptions of the devices connected to the available serial ports. If there is a match, returns the system-defined port name (e.g. COM1, ttyS0,...) for that port. Otherwise, returns an empty string. If you are implementing this method and for some reason you can't obtain the device descriptions, you have two options:
         1. Match the regular expression to the system-defined port names of all the available serial ports with connected devices (e.g. COM1, ttyS0,...).
         2. Return always an empty string.
        Parameters:
        regularExpression - Regular experession to be matched.
        Returns:
        The system-defined port name of the matched device. If there is no match, an empty string.
